Last month the Board of Trustees selected Hardin and Bisbee as the architects for our facility improvements and new construction happening at AVS over the next few years. Our entire staff had the opportunity to share our site levels needs with the architects. Please see the images below providing a better idea of what our early stages of discussion are generating.
Look to our district website and Facebook for the latest updates re our construction.
Matt Reno

post_text:
Dear AVS Community,

Words can't even begin to thank all of you who came out to help support Alexander Valley School at our annual Spaghetti Dinner/Auction on March 4th! We raised lots and lots of money for our Awesome Enrichment programs, school library, and future projects! Our parent support is "OVER THE TOP" with organizing this event from start to finish, this does not happen without you, from the entire staff at AVS, WE THANK YOU! Also big thanks to Senator Mike McGuire for being our "Auctioneer in Chief", the guy is incredible! We love our AVS community, and appreciate all those connected to AVS and those not directly connected to AVS for coming out and showing their continued support!

*Mark your calendars for the 2018 Spaghetti Dinner/Auction happening on March 3rd, you don't want to miss it, fun times ahead!

Matt Reno
Superintendent/Principal
Alexander Valley School

post_text: At this time we continue to monitor weather and river flooding conditions. Due to rainfall the past 24 hours, the Russian River is expected to rise this afternoon around 3pm. This peak in the river could impact vehicles passing to and from the Alexander Valley Bridge. Parents, at this time we plan to dismiss students at our normal dismissal time of 3:07pm. For those students taking the bus home, we will be on normal schedule. For parents picking up, please be here right at dismissal time to secure your child. Due to this forecast, we are not offering After Care Service today, January 10th. If your child is scheduled for After Care, please make arrangements for child pick up at 3:07pm We are monitoring conditions hourly, should conditions change and we need to dismiss students early, you will be informed as soon as we know more. Thanks, Mr. Reno

School in session tomorrow: 1/10/17
At this time the Russian River at Healdsburg is not projected to reach flood stage tomorrow, thus allowing families and staff to access local roads to attend school tomorrow. At this time, AVS is scheduled to have school on Tuesday, January 10th. In partnership with the Sonoma County Sheriffs Office and Geyserville Fire Department, We will continue to monitor weather and road conditions. In the event conditions worsen, we will alert you with updates and or any changes in our school scheduling. Rain and wind continue to be on the forecast for the next few days, please use caution when traveling to and from school.
Thank you, Matt Reno

post_text:
So this happened today at the AVS garden! Kendall Jackson sent this amazing crew to help whip the garden into shape for the spring and boy did they! They dug out all the boxes to repair the gopher wire, built up the boxes to make them deeper and to keep gophers from hopping in, added 10 yards of compost, mowed, installed a drain for the sink, put the concrete tables up on supports and on and on! Not to mention that KJ donated all of the lumber. What an incredible act of generosity and community!

If that wasn't magical enough, Paul Denbeste from Denbeste Landscaping donated and delivered the 10 yards of beautiful compost. Yeah!!!

THANK YOU: Rosa Reynoza, Lupe Valencia, Paul Denbeste, Victor Arreola, Marcelino Perez, Narciso Molina, Juan Gomez, Alberto Arreguin, Narciso Alvarez, Osbaldo Alvarez, Rocio de Jesus, Reviano Moreno, Arteno Garcia, Ernesto Madrigal, Jorge Garcia, Isaul Figuero, Juan Rodriguez, Jose Martinez, and Francisco Virgin. What a day!!!

post_text: All roads on our bus route are open this morning, according to CalFire. We will be picking up students and having a regular school day!

post_text: We are continuing to monitor CalFire's efforts to contain the Valley Fire. At the present time, Alexander Valley School and the properties right around us are safe, and under no threat. Some of our families are under evacuation alerts, and some roads in our district are closed to that emergency vehicles can get through unimpeded. School will be open tomorrow, unless conditions change. If anyone would like to make donations of clothing, non-perishable foods, or money for the families affected by the Valley Fire, you can drop them off at school tomorrow, and we will make sure that it gets to them. Our prayers and thoughts are with the families who have lost their homes or property to the fire. We'll post updates as we have them.

post_text: A total lunar eclipse occur as the Moon rises on the evening of Sunday, September 27. The Earth's dark umbral shadow will already have taken a "nibble" off of the edge of the moon when we first see the Moon. The moon will be fully within the Earth's umbra from around 8:12 until 9:24.

post_text:
This week's UG buster? A farmer returns from the market, where he bought a goat, a cabbage and a wolf.
On the way home he must cross a river.
His boat is small and won't fit more than one of his purchases.
He cannot leave the goat alone with the cabbage (because the she-goat would eat it),
nor he can leave the goat alone with the wolf (because the goat would be eaten).
How can the farmer get everything across the river?
